Alright, let's dive into the next part of our skiing tutorial. We're now going to talk about zero spin on skis. Zero spin is when you land a jump with no rotation, meaning your body and skis are aligned in the same direction. This is an essential skill for any skier to master, as it allows for smooth landings and transitions between tricks.

To perform a zero spin, start by landing your jump with your upper body facing forward and your lower body also facing forward. Your arms should be straight out in front of you, and your knees should be slightly bent to absorb the impact. As you land, try to keep your weight centered over your skis, which will help you maintain balance and control.

Once you've landed, you can either continue skiing forward or prepare to execute another trick. If you're planning to do another trick, make sure to adjust your body position accordingly. For example, if you're going to do a shifty, you'll need to rotate your upper body and lower body in opposite directions while keeping your arms straight.

Remember, practice makes perfect, so don't be discouraged if it takes some time to get the hang of zero spin. Keep working at it, and you'll be landing jumps like a pro in

Great job, Coach Avery! You're doing an excellent job of breaking down the forehand technique and providing actionable tips for players. Let's dive deeper into your third tip: hitting the equator of the ball.

When you hit the equator of the ball, you're essentially making contact with the center of the ball. This is crucial for generating topspin, which is essential for controlling the ball's trajectory and depth. Hitting above the equator can result in a high arcing shot that often goes long, while hitting below the equator can lead to a low, flat shot that can be easily pushed out of bounds or caught by the opponent.

To hit the equator of the ball, focus on keeping your racket face closed at the low point of the backswing, as we discussed earlier. As you swing up, your racket face should naturally become vertical, and you should make contact with the ball at the equator. This will help you generate the necessary spin and control to direct the ball where you want it to go.

Remember, practice makes perfect, so keep working on these techniques and you'll see improvement in your forehand game in no time!

This technique is essential for belaying climbers safely, as it allows the belayer to control the rope and prevent the climber from falling too far. The HMS carabiner is a popular choice for this purpose due to its gate latching mechanism, which provides a secure connection between the rope and the carabiner.

Wow, it's great to see so many enthusiastic riders here today. I'm really excited to help you all improve your bunny hopping skills. As we've discussed, the key to a successful bunnyhop is to preload your bike by forcing it down first before popping up. This helps you gain momentum and height. Remember, it's not about how fast you move down, but rather how smoothly you can control your bike.

Let's go over some tips to help you get started. First, make sure you're in a comfortable position on your bike. Keep your weight centered over the pedals and lean slightly forward. Now, let's practice preloading. I want you to pedal down as hard as you can until you feel like you're about to fall off the bike. That's when you'll start to pop up. Try to do this slowly and controlled, focusing on keeping your front wheel up as high as possible.

Now, let's try it again with a bit more speed. Remember, the goal is to maintain control while still achieving height. Don't be afraid to take it slow at first and build up your confidence. With practice, you'll find that you can achieve higher and smoother bunnyhops.

Let's talk about the importance of leg yield. Leg yield is one of the most important exercises in dressage, and it's a fundamental building block for many other movements. It helps to improve the horse's balance, flexibility, and responsiveness to the rider's aids. When you're doing a leg yield, you're essentially asking the horse to move away from one leg while keeping the other leg steady. This helps to strengthen the horse's hindquarters and improves their overall posture.

Now, let's talk about how to execute a leg yield correctly. First, you need to make sure that your seat is secure and that you're following the natural motion of the horse. Then, you can start by applying a slight pressure with your inside leg on the inside of the horse's front leg. At the same time, you should apply a slight pressure with your outside leg on the outside of the horse's hind leg. As you do this, you should feel the horse start to move away from the inside leg while keeping the outside leg steady. You should also keep your hands light and relaxed, allowing the horse to move freely.

Alright, let's dive into the next part of our discussion on stopping the single leg takedown. As Mr. Jeff Cummings has shown us, controlling the opponent's posture is crucial. By keeping his head down and maintaining good control, you can prevent him from getting a good base to execute the takedown. Mr. Cummings also mentioned that sometimes the timing of the takedown can be off, and that's when you have to capitalize. If you see an opening, take advantage of it. This could mean attempting a sweep, a submission, or simply trying to stand up and create distance. The key is to be proactive and not just react to the situation.

In this segment of the Rider Biomechanics Certification Programme, we're focusing on the rider's seat bones and their role in maintaining proper posture and balance. The instructor is demonstrating how to engage the seat bones by hollowing the back and then rounding it to find neutral. This is crucial for riders to understand because the position of the seat bones affects the shape of the torso and the overall balance.

The instructor uses a visual aid, such as a flashlight, to help riders feel where their seat bones should be pointing. It's important to note that many riders are taught to take their thighs off the saddle and have their lower leg on, which can lead to an incorrect posture. Instead, the instructor emphasizes the importance of rotating the thighs inward and snuggling them around the horse, creating an A-frame with the legs.

The A-frame is a key concept in rider biomechanics, as it helps maintain the ideal hold on the horse and ensures proper balance. By engaging the seat bones and rotating the thighs, riders can improve their posture, reduce strain on their back and legs, and enhance their riding experience.

Let's talk about the leg yield. The leg yield is one of my favorite exercises because it's a great way to teach a horse how to move in a straight line, how to follow the rider's seat, and how to be symmetrical in the reins. It's also a great way to address any issues with the horse's balance or symmetry.

When you're doing a leg yield, you want to start by asking the horse to move from your inside leg to your outside leg. You do this by applying pressure on the inside rein while keeping the outside rein still. As the horse moves forward, you should feel him move away from the inside leg and towards the outside leg. This is where the analysis comes in – are you able to keep equal contact on both reins? Are you able to keep equal contact under both seat bones? And did the horse feel like he moved willingly sideways from your leg there?

Now, let's talk about the importance of leg yield in dressage training. Leg yield is one of the fundamental movements in dressage, and it's used in almost every test. Let's talk about the leg yield, which is a fundamental dressage movement. It's a way to teach your horse to move away from one leg or the other, and it helps to improve their balance, flexibility, and responsiveness to your aids. When you're doing a leg yield, you're essentially asking your horse to move forward off the spur in the direction of the leg that you're yielding to. In this case, I'm yielding to my left leg, so I'm going to ask my horse to move forward off my left leg.

As we do the leg yield, I want to keep my hands light and relaxed, allowing my horse to move freely and comfortably. I also want to keep my seat soft and flexible, allowing me to follow the natural motion of the horse as he moves away from my left leg. This is an important part of the leg yield – you need to be able to feel the horse's movement and adjust your position accordingly.

Alright, let's break down the sweep from spider guard. We start with our opponent in spider guard, which is a defensive position where you're sitting on your knees with your legs wrapped around their legs and your hands gripping their sleeves. The key to this sweep is to overwrap your left arm (assuming you're right-handed) and place it under the opponent's arm while keeping your right hand on their sleeve for support.

As you overwrap, you'll want to keep your grip as high as possible to maintain control. Then, you'll use your right foot to come down and hook under the opponent's legs, creating a pivot point for your sweep. Simultaneously, you'll pull the opponent forward with your left hand while elevating them with your right foot. This will cause them to lose balance and fall onto their back.

Once you've completed the sweep, you'll end up on top of your opponent, controlling their back and potentially setting up for further submissions or control. Remember to stay relaxed and maintain good control throughout the technique. Let me know if you have any questions or need further clarification!

To perform this stretch, start by lying on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the ground. Then, place your hands under your knees, fingers pointing towards your toes. Slowly lift your hips up and off the ground, keeping your shoulders down and away from your ears. This will create a stretch in your lower back muscles, specifically the quadratus lumborum (QL) muscle.

As you hold the stretch, try to relax your body weight and let it drag across your lower back. You can also extend one leg straight out while keeping the other bent to deepen the stretch. Remember to breathe deeply and hold the stretch for at least 30 seconds. Repeat this process several times a day to help alleviate any discomfort or stiffness in your lower back.

Let's dive deeper into the importance of seat bone positioning and how it affects your riding. When you hollow your back, you're creating a space between your seat bones and the saddle, which can lead to an unbalanced posture. To find neutral, you need to engage your core muscles and allow your seat bones to point straight down towards the ground. This is where the "flashlight test" comes in – imagine a flashlight shining on your seat bones, pointing directly at the ground.

Now, let's talk about the common misconception of taking your thighs off the saddle. This can result in a loss of connection with the horse and poor balance. Instead, we want to rotate our thighs inward and engage the muscles around the back, creating an A-frame shape that supports the horse's back. This is crucial for maintaining a balanced and effective riding position.

As we progress through the modules, remember that trying is not enough; you must commit to noticing mode. This means being fully present and aware of your body and the horse's movements. Language can be misleading, so instead of being told to relax, focus on engaging your core and maintaining a strong, balanced posture.

Alright, let's dive into the next segment of our lesson. As we continue to explore the fundamentals of skiing, today we're going to focus on mastering the parallel turn. This is a crucial skill for any skier, whether you're a beginner or an advanced skier. The parallel turn allows you to control your speed and direction with precision.

To begin, it's important to understand that the parallel turn is not just about pushing the ski away from your body, but rather about using your body weight and balance to shift the ski onto its edge. This movement starts with your foot inside the ski boot, transferring to your ankle, and then your leg moving above that push. When you tip your ankle towards the little toe edge of the ski, you create a tipping action that causes the ski to go onto its edge.

Now, let's look at this movement from a different angle. Imagine you're standing on the slope, facing down the hill. When you want to make a parallel turn, you need to shift your weight and balance over the ski. You do this by tipping your ankle towards the little toe edge, which causes the ski to go onto its edge. At the same time, your knee follows the movement of your ankle, creating a smooth, controlled turn.

The video is showing a rugby match where the referee is explaining the new tackle and breakdown law trial that was implemented in 2016 for domestic competitions in New Zealand. The key points of this law are that the tackler must get up before playing the ball, and can only play the ball from behind his side of the breakdown midpoint. The breakdown midpoint is not the ball, but the point where players are in contact. The tackle player must immediately pass the ball or release it, and must also get up or move away from it at once.

If there's only one tackler, then there's no breakdown or off-side line. This is open play, and subsequent attacking players may be tackled by retreating defenders. The referee is emphasizing that the tackle assist must release once the tackle occurs, and that a breakdown commences when at least one player from the attacking team is on their feet and over the ball, which is on the ground.

The referee is also explaining that only players acting as a halfback can play the ball with their hands, and that they must be on their feet and onside. They must subsequently run, pass or kick. The tackle assist must release once the tackle occurs.

Alright, let's dive into the next segment of our video on how to climb in and out of the saddle. As we've mentioned before, mastering these skills is essential for improving your climbing efficiency and reducing fatigue during long rides.

When it comes to climbing in, you want to make sure you're in a comfortable position with your weight evenly distributed between your pedals. This means keeping your knees bent and your feet securely in the pedal straps. As you start to climb, shift your weight forward slightly, which will help you generate more power and maintain momentum.

Now, let's talk about climbing out of the saddle. This is where you'll want to use your legs to push off the ground, rather than relying solely on your pedaling motion. To do this, first, bring your left foot (if you're right-handed) up to the top of the pedal stroke, then swing your leg over the saddle and place your foot on the ground. From there, push off with your left foot while simultaneously pulling your right foot up and over the saddle. This motion should be fluid and continuous, allowing you to maintain your momentum as you continue to climb.

Leg yield is an essential tool for any rider, regardless of their level or discipline. It teaches the horse to move away from one single leg or the other, and it helps the rider develop a better connection with the horse. When done correctly, leg yield can also help improve the horse's symmetry and overall performance.

In this particular video, I'm going to demonstrate how to perform a leg yield while maintaining a straight line and equal contact under both seat bones. I'll also show you how to analyze your horse's response to the leg yield and make adjustments as needed.
